  "diary": "Woke up early and made myself a proper espresso—the good stuff, not that instant nonsense. The rain was already coming down pretty hard when I left Madison Valley. Got lucky with the commute, though I heard later that the 520 bridge was a complete nightmare. By the time I hit SoDo, the worst had passed.\n\nSpent the morning doing what I love: milling grain, getting the mash just right. There's something meditative about it, especially on a grey day like this. The fermentation tanks were humming along nicely. Grabbed lunch at Fuel Cafe—quick espresso and a sandwich—and honestly, it was the perfect reset before tackling the afternoon shift.\n\nQuality checks went smooth. The rain cleared up on my drive home, which felt like a small gift. Cooked some rice and dal, watched a bit of telly, then lost myself in some gaming. Felt good to just be still after being on my feet all day.",
  "thought_process": "The morning routine steadies me—espresso is non-negotiable. I knew the rain might complicate the commute, so I left early, which turned out to be smart thinking. The bridge closure was all over the news, but SoDo wasn't as affected, so I got in without too much hassle. Work felt purposeful today; the brewing process absorbed my attention completely, which is exactly what I needed. I skipped any elaborate lunch plans because I wanted to stay focused on the afternoon's QC checks. Once I left the brewery and saw the clouds breaking up, my mood lifted considerably. The commute home felt like the day finally exhaling. I opted for cooking rather than ordering—wanted something familiar and grounding. By evening, I was ready to decompress with gaming, nothing too demanding. The weather shift, the smooth drive home—these small things shaped how I moved through the day.",
